==English==
{{wp}}

===Etymology===
16th century, {{bor+|en|la|thēsaurus|nocap=1}}, from {{der|en|grc|θησαυρός||storehouse, treasure}}; its current English usage/meaning was established soon after the publication of Peter Roget's ''Thesaurus of English Words and Phrases'' in 1852. {{doublet|en|treasure}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/θɪˈsɔːɹəs/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-thesaurus.wav|a=Southern England}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɔːɹəs|s=3}}
* {{hyph|en|the|saur|us}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|thesauri|+}}

# {{senseid|en|type of wordbook, especially for synonyms}} A [[publication]] that provides [[synonym]]s (and sometimes [[antonym]]s and other {{l|en|semantic}} relations) for the [[word]]s of a given [[language]].
#: {{syn|en|synonymicon|wordhoard}}
#: {{ux|en|"Roget" is the leading brand name for a print English '''thesaurus''' that lists words under general concepts rather than just close synonyms.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 18, 2008|author=Charles Mcgrath|title=The Keeper (See: Steward, Caretaker) of Synonyms|work=New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/18/books/18book.html|passage=As reference books go, the '''thesaurus''' has had a somewhat checkered history, in fact, and has probably occasioned as much bad writing as good.}}
# {{senseid|en|dictionary or encyclopedia, archaically}} {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[dictionary]] or [[encyclopedia]].
# {{senseid|en|hierarchy of subject headings}} {{lb|en|information science}} A [[hierarchy]] of [[subject]] [[heading]]s: [[canonical]] titles of [[theme]]s and [[topic]]s, the titles serving as search keys.
