{{en-verb}}

# To confine in, or as in, a pound; to [[impound]].
#* {{c.|1620}}, anonymous, “{{w|Tom o' Bedlam|Tom o’ Bedlam’s Song}}” in ''Giles Earle his Booke'' (British Museum, Additional MSS. 24, 665):
#*: When I short haue shorne my sowce face<br>& swigg’d my horny barrell,<br>In an oaken Inne I '''pound''' my skin<br>as a suite of guilt apparrell
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1644|author=w:John Milton|title={{w|Areopagitica}}; A speech of Mr. John Milton for the Liberty of Unlicenc’d Printing, to the Parlament of England|passage=And he who were pleasantly disposed, could not well avoid to liken it to the exploit of that gallant man, who thought to '''pound''' up the crows by shutting his park gate.}}

===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{m|en|poun}}, {{m|en|pown}}, from {{inh|en|enm|pounen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|pūnian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*pūn-|t=broken pieces, rubble}}. Related to {{cog|stq|Pün|t=debris, fragments}}, {{cog|fy|pún|t=debris, rubble}}, {{cog|nl|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish}}, {{cog|nds|pun||fragments}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|en|poun}}, {{alt|en|pown}} {{qualifier|obsolete or dialectal}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[strike]] [[hard]], usually [[repeated]]ly.
#: {{syn|en|hammer|pelt|Thesaurus:hit}}
#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=12|passage=She had Lord James' collar in one big fist and she '''pounded''' the table with the other and talked a blue streak. Nobody could make out plain what she said, for she was mainly jabbering Swede lingo, but there was English enough, of a kind, to give us some idee.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=December|title=Talking of Trains: The railways and the Devon floods|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=709|text=[...] and on the Saturday heavy seas '''pounded''' the W.R. on its exposed coastal stretch between Dawlish and Teignmouth, loosening the ballast and forcing trains to proceed with extreme caution.}}
#* {{quote-song|en|author=w:Bob Dylan|year=1964|title=Motorpsycho Nitemare|passage=I '''pounded''' on a farmhouse / Lookin' for a place to stay / I was mighty, mighty tired / I had come a long, long way}}
# {{senseid|en|to crush}} {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[crush]] to pieces; to [[pulverize]].
#: {{syn|en|pulverate|triturate}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1887|title=Indian Cookery "Local" for Young Housekeepers: Second Edition|page=67
|passage='''Pound''' an onion, warm a spoonful of ghee and throw in the onion, brown it slightly, add your curry stuff, brown this till it smells pleasantly, {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Roots: The Saga of an American Family|chapter=1|author=w:Alex Haley|year=1976|passage=It was the hour before the first crowing of the cocks, and along with Nyo Boto and Grandma Yaisa's clattering, the first sound the child heard was the muted, rhythmic bombpabombpabomp of wooden pestles as the other women of the village '''pounded''' couscous grain in their mortars, preparing the traditional breakfast of porridge that was cooked in earthen pots over a fire built among three rocks.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To [[eat]] or [[drink]] very [[quickly]].
#: {{syn|en|bolt|down|chug|Thesaurus:eat|Thesaurus:drink}}
#: {{ux|en|You really '''pounded''' that beer!}}
#* {{quote-song|en|year=2007|title=Fire Marshall Willy|artist=The Dreadnoughts|passage=The sounds of a house-party rolled down the street / So we '''pounded''' our Pilsner and leapt to our feet}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|baseball|slang}} To [[pitch]] [[consistently]] to a certain location.
#: {{ux|en|The pitcher has been '''pounding''' the outside corner all night.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a body part, generally heart, blood, or head}} To [[beat]] [[strongly]] or [[throb]].
#: {{ux|en|As I tiptoed past the sleeping dog, my heart was '''pounding''' but I remained silent.}}
#: {{ux|en|My head was '''pounding'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1936|title=The Short, Happy Life of Francis Macomber|author=w:Ernest Hemingway|passage=It was now about three o’clock in the morning and Francis Macomber, who had been asleep a little while after he had stopped thinking about the lion, wakened and then slept again, woke suddenly, frightened in a dream of the bloody-headed lion standing over him, and listening while his heart '''pounded''', he realized that his wife was not in the other cot in the tent.}}
#* {{quote-song|en|author=w:Rachel Platten;w:[[Dave Bassett (songwriter)|Dave Bassett]];w:[[Brian West (record producer)|Brian West]]|authorlabel=no|title=Beating Me Up|album=w:[[Fight Song (EP)|Fight Song]]|date=12 May 2015|artist=Rachel Platten|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SI9tDIEnalA|text=I can't let go, you're like the chemical<br>You're racing through me<br>My heart just '''pounds''', '''pounds''', '''pounds'''...}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|vulgar|slang}} To [[penetrate]] [[sexual]]ly, with [[vigour]].
#: {{syn|en|drill|get up in|nail|poke|Thesaurus:copulate with}}
#: {{ux|en|I was '''pounding''' her all night!}}
#* {{quote-song|en|title=Bachelor Pad|album=The Movie|author=w:Gucci Mane|year=2008|passage=She acting, so I'm attacking, try break the mattress / Sexy, so I suggested to switch to sideways / '''Pounded''' for 'bout a hour she said she tired}}
# To advance heavily with measured steps.
#* {{RQ:Conrad Heart of Darkness|part=I|passage=We '''pounded''' along, stopped, landed soldiers; went on, landed custom–house clerks to levy toll in what looked like a God–forsaken wilderness, with a tin shed and a flag–pole lost in it; landed more soldiers—to take care of the custom–house clerks, presumably.}}
# {{lb|en|engineering}} To make a [[jarring]] [[noise]], as when running.
#: {{ux|en|The engine '''pounds'''.}}

