====Declension====
{{pl-decl-noun-m-anml|p|s|pies|dats=psu}}
* The accusative singular form {{m|pl|piesa}} is found in the {{w|Near Masovian dialect}} ({{w|Warka}}, {{w|Czersk}})
* The dative singular form {{m|pl|psowi}} is found in the {{w|Podhale dialect}} ({{w|Rabka-Zdrój}}) and the {{w|Eastern Kraków dialect}} ({{w|Gdów}}, {{w|Bochnia}})
* The nominative plural form {{m|pl|psi}} is found most often in folk songs, usually as part of a rhyme, but not always, in the {{w|Kuyavian dialect}} ({{w|Brdów}}, {{w|Kowal}}, {{w|Więcławice}}); the {{w|Near Masovian dialect}} ({{w|Łukowiec, Masovian Voivodeship}}, {{w|Warsaw}}, {{w|Parysów}}, {{w|Łukowiec}}); the {{w|Łęczyca dialect}} ({{w|Smardzew}}, {{w|Topola}}), the {{w|Lasovia dialect}} ({{w|Tarnobrzeg}}), the {{w|Kielce dialect}}, the {{w|Western Kraków dialect}} ({{w|Zebrzydowice}}, {{w|Modlnica}}), the {{w|Eastern Kraków dialect}} ({{w|Gdów}}, {{w|Bochnia}}), the {{w|Western Lublin dialect}} ({{w|Puławy}}), the {{w|Babia Góra dialect}} ({{w|Maków Podhalański}})
* In the {{w|Far Masovian dialect}} ({{w|Przasnysz}}), the word may take masculine personal declension, e.g. ''Wzion zara trzech {{m|pl|psów}}''.

