# {{senseid|en|Q8335}}{{lb|en|countable}} Any of several, generally [[large#Adjective|large]], [[species]] of [[bird#Noun|birds]] in the [[genus]] ''[[Corvus]]'' with [[lustrous]] [[black#Adjective|black]] [[plumage]]; especially the [[common raven]] ({{taxfmt|Corvus corax|species}}).
#: {{hyper|en|bird|corvid}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Titus Andronicus Q1|act=II|scene=iii|sig=D3|verso=1|page=27|passage=Some ſay that '''Rauens''' foſter forlorne children, / The vvhilſt their ovvne birds famiſh in their neſts: / Oh be to me though thy hard hart ſay no, / Nothing ſo kinde but ſomething pittifull.}}
#* {{RQ:Marlowe Jew of Malta|sig=D2|page=30|passage=Thus like the ſad preſaging '''Rauen''' that tolls / The ſick mans paſſeport in her hollovv beake, / And in the ſhadovv of the ſilent night / Doth ſhake contagion from her ſable vvings; / Vex'd and tormented runnes poore ''Barabas'' / VVith fatall curſes tovvards theſe Chriſtians.}}
#* {{RQ:Camden Holland Britain|chapter=Denshire|page=207|passage=[T]he Danes bare in their Enſigne a '''Raven''' vvrought (by report) in needle-vvorke, by the daughters of Lothbroke that is, ''Leather-breech'', {{...}}|footer=Compare {{senseno|en|flag}}.}}
#* {{RQ:Guillim Heraldrie|chapter=Sect{{quote-gloss|ion}} III. Chap{{quote-gloss|ter}} XX.|page=162|passage=Hee beareth ''Or'', a '''''Rauen''' Proper'', by the name of ''Corbet''.|footer=Used as a charge on a coat of arms.}}
#* {{RQ:Shelley Poetical Works|volume=III|poem=Similes|stanza=1|page=189|passage=As from an ancestral oak / Two empty '''ravens''' sound their clarion, / Yell by yell, and croak by croak, / When they scent the noonday smoke / Of fresh human carrion: {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Scott Pirate|volume=I|chapter=V|page=117|passage=If the men of Thule have ceased to be champions, and to spread the banquet for the '''raven''', the women have not forgotten the arts that lifted them of yore into queens and prophetesses.}}
#* {{RQ:Audubon Ornithological Biography|chapter=A Flood|pages=157–158|pageref=158|passage=All is silent and melancholy, unless when the mournful bleeting of the hemmed in Deer reaches your ear, or the dismal scream of an Eagle or a '''Raven''' is heard, as the foul bird rises, disturbed by your approach, from the carcass on which it was allaying its craving appetite.}}
#* {{RQ:Dickens Barnaby Rudge|chapter=6|page=270|passage=The '''raven''', with his head very much on one side, and his bright eye shining like a diamond, preserved a thoughtful silence for a few seconds, and then replied in a voice so hoarse and distant, that it seemed to come through his thick feathers rather than out of his mouth. "Halloa, halloa, halloa! What's the matter here! Keep up your spirits. Never say die. Bow wow wow. I'm a devil, I'm a devil, I'm a devil. Hurrah!"}}
#* {{RQ:Poe Raven|page=144|passage="Though thy crest be shorn and shaven, thou," I said, "art sure no craven, / Ghastly grim and ancient '''raven''' wandering from the Nightly shore— / Tell me what thy lordly name is on the Night's Plutonian shore!" / Quoth the '''raven''', "Nevermore."}}
#* {{RQ:Lowell Fable for Critics|page=57|passage=There comes [[w:Edgar Allan Poe|Poe]] with his '''raven''', like {{w|Barnaby Rudge}}, / Three-fifths of him genius and two-fifths fudge, / {{...}} / Who has written some things quite the best of their kind, / But the heart somehow seems all squeezed out by the mind, {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Tennyson Idylls|page=232|passage=A blot in heaven, the '''Raven''', flying high, / Croak'd, and she thought 'he spies a field of death; / For now the Heathen of the Northern Sea, / Lured by the crimes and frailties of the court, / Begin to slay the folk, and spoil the land.'}}
## {{senseid|en|Q115702282}} {{lb|en|uncountable}} A [[jet-black]], often [[glossy#Adjective|glossy]], [[color#Noun|colour]], like that of the plumage of a raven ''({{senseno|en|Q8335}})''.
##: {{color panel|07090A}}
##: {{nearsyn|en|ebony#Noun|onyx#Noun}}
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1859|author=Ferna Vale|chapter=Alone|title=Natalie; or, A Gem among the Sea-weeds|location=Andover, Mass.|publisher={{...|Printed by}} W[arren] F. Draper|page=314|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/natalieorgemamon00valeiala/natalieorgemamon00valeiala/page/n319/mode/1up|oclc=36254678|passage=A lone man walks the shores of Nantucket; his noble form is slightly bent, and with the '''raven''' of his hair is blended the faintest tinge of gray, though he is evidently a man to whom the meridian of life is yet far in the distance; {{...}}}}
## {{lb|en|archaic|countable}} ''Usually preceded by a [[descriptive#Adjective|descriptive]] [[word#Noun|word]]'': a bird from a genus other than ''Corvus'' that [[resemble]]s the raven ''({{senseno|en|Q8335}})'', especially in having black plumage; also, an [[imaginary#Adjective|imaginary]] black bird.
##* {{RQ:Goldsmith History of the Earth|volume=VI|chapter=Of the Auk, Puffin, and Other Birds of the Penguin Kind|pages=92–93|pageref=92|passage=VVhen the great ſea-'''raven''', as Jacobſon informs us, comes to take avvay their young, the puffins boldly oppoſe him. {{...}} As ſoon as the '''raven''' approaches, the puffin catches him under the throat vvith its beak, and ſticks its clavvs into his breaſt, vvhich makes the '''raven''', vvith a loud ſcreaming, attempt to get avvay; {{...}}}}
##* {{RQ:Shelley Poetical Works|edition=revised|volume=II|poem=Victoria|stanza=I|page=500|passage=Along the wild mountains night-'''ravens''' were yelling— / They bodingly presaged destruction and woe.}}
## {{senseid|en|flag}}{{lb|en|historical|countable}} A [[flag#Noun|flag]] [[bear#Verb|bearing]] a raven ''({{senseno|en|Q8335}})'', formerly [[use#Verb|used]] by some [[Viking#Noun|Viking]] [[leader]]s
### {{lb|en|uncountable|metonymic}} ''preceded by'' '''[[the#Article|the]]''': Viking [[military#Adjective|military]] [[power#Noun|power]].
###* {{RQ:Thomson Mallet Alfred|scene=iii|page=36|passage=Behold the vvarrior bright vvith ''Daniſh'' ſpoils!— / The '''''raven''''' droops his vvings—and hark! the trumpet, / Exulting, ſpeaks the reſt.}}
## {{lb|en|chiefly|fiction|countable}} A [[person#Noun|person]], especially a [[man#Noun|man]], with black [[hair#Noun|hair]].
##: {{coordinate terms|en|ravenette<q:rare>}}
# {{lb|en|countable|figurative|obsolete}} A person who [[bring#Verb|brings]] [[bad#Adjective|bad]] [[news#Noun|news]] or [[make#Verb|makes]] [[pessimistic]] [[prediction]]s.
#* {{RQ:Rowley New Wonder|page=47|passage=''Ric''{{quote-gloss|''hard''}}. Novv y'ave ſpoke it halfe; 'tis ſinking I muſt treate of; / Your ſhips are all ſunke. / {{...}} / ''M''{{quote-gloss|''istress''}} ''Foſt''{{quote-gloss|''er''}}. O thou fatall '''Raven'''; Let me pull thine eyes out for this / Sad croake.}}
#* {{RQ:Dryden Lee Duke of Guise|scene=i|page=53|passage=''Mal''{{quote-gloss|''icorn''}}. O my dear Lord, upon this onely day / Depends the ſeries of your follovving Fate: / Think your good Genius has aſſum'd my ſhape / In this Prophetick doom. / ''Guiſe''. Peace croaking '''Raven''', / I'le ſeize him firſt, then make him a led Monarch; {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Burke State of the Nation|page=33|passage=Some '''ravens''' have alvvays indeed croaked out this kind of ſong. They have a malignant delight in preſaging miſchief vvhen they are not employed in doing it: they are miſerable and diſapointed at every inſtance of the public proſperity.}}

