## {{lb|en|transitive}}
### {{lb|en|archaic}} ''Sometimes followed by'' '''[[away#Adverb|away]]''' ''or'' '''[[from]]''': to [[obtain]] or [[seize]] (something, especially [[property#Noun|property]]) by [[force#Noun|force]] or [[violence#Noun|violence]]; to [[plunder#Verb|plunder]].
###* {{RQ:Sleidanus Daus Commentaries|book=XXIJ|folio=ccclv|verso=1|folioend=ccclvj|folioref=ccclvj|passage={{quote-gloss|They}} aſſaulted by night a certen aũciẽt {{quote-gloss|auncient}} gentleman at home in his owne houſe, which had done thē {{quote-gloss|them}} no diſpleaſure, and being a ſlepe in his bed at their cõming {{quote-gloss|comming}}, whan he had hardly eſcaped awaye half naked, '''rauening''' and diſtroying his goodes, they ſpoyled his wyfe and chyldren of all theyr apparell, and threatening them ofte with death, left thẽ {{quote-gloss|them}} ſtarck naked, in ſo muche that one of the Nobilitie comming thither by chaunce, couered the woman with his owne garment.}}
### {{lb|en|archaic}} ''Sometimes followed by'' '''[[down#Preposition|down]]''''','' '''[[up#Preposition|up]]''''', or'' {{lb|en|obsolete}} '''[[in#Preposition|in]]''': to [[eat#Verb|eat]] (something, such as [[food]] or [[prey#Noun|prey]]) [[greedily]]; to [[devour]], to [[wolf down]].
###* {{RQ:Geneva Bible|Ezekiel|XXII|27|folio=343|column=2|passage=Her princes in the middes thereof ''are'' like vvolues, '''rauening''' y&#868; pray {{quote-gloss|prey}} to ſhed blood, ''and'' to ſhed blood, ''and'' to deſtroye ſoules for their ovvne couetous lucre.}}
###* {{RQ:Knolles Turkes|chapter=The Life of [[w:Selim II|Selymus, the Second of that Name]], Fift Emperour of the Turkes|page=833|passage=[C]ertaine young men vvhom they call Giamoglans, vvith others that ſtood round about them, ſnatcht it {{quote-gloss|the food}} haſtily vp as their fees, and like greedie Harpies '''rauened''' it dovvne in a moment.}}
###* {{RQ:Topsell Foure-footed Beastes|chapter=Of Handling, Taming, or Breaking of Horsses|page=303|passage=In the morning giue them {{quote-gloss|horses}} barley or prouender, a little at a time in diſtinct or ſeueral portions, tvvice or thrice one after another, ſo as he may chevv and eke diſgeſt it thoroughly, othervviſe if he '''rauen''' it, as he vvil do hauing much at a time, he rendreth it in his dung vvhole and not diſgeſted.}}
###* {{RQ:Brathwait Strappado|part=Loves Labyrinth|poem=Pyramus and Thysbe|page=40|passage=A Lion nevv returnde from '''rauening''' pray {{quote-gloss|prey}}, / came to the fount, his blood to vvaſh avvay.}}
###* {{RQ:Rabelais Gargantua|volume=I|book=2|chapter=How Pantagruel Found Panurge, whom He Loved All His Lifetime|pages=211–212|pageref=212|passage=[A]t this present I am in a very urgent necessity to feed, {{...}} if you will but set me to work, it will be as good as a balsamum for sore eyes to see me gulch and '''raven''' it, for Gods sake, give order for it.}}
###* {{RQ:Dante Cary Vision|volume=I|canto=XXXII|lines=122–127|page=143|passage={{...}} I beheld two spirits by the ice / Pent in one hollow, that the head of one / Was cowl unto the other; and as bread / Is '''raven'd''' up through hunger, th' uppermost / Did so apply his fangs to th' other's brain, / Where the spine joins it.}}
###* {{RQ:Keats Endymion|lines=514–515|page=130|passage=Clusters of grapes, the which they '''raven'd''' quick / And roar'd for more; {{...}}}}
### {{lb|en|figurative}} To [[absorb]] or [[take in]] (something, such as [[information]]) greedily; also, to [[approach#Verb|approach]] or [[pounce#Verb|pounce]] on (someone) like prey.
###* {{RQ:Lowell Three Memorial Poems|page=22|passage=[S]he fenced them in their need / With iron-handed Duty's sternest creed, / 'Gainst Self's lean wolf that '''ravens''' word and deed.}}
###* {{RQ:D. Smith Castle|pages=55–56|pageref=55|passage=But some characters in books are very real—{{w|Jane Austen}}'s are; and I know those five Bennets at the opening of ''{{w|Pride and Prejudice}}'', simply waiting to '''raven''' the young men at Netherfield Park, are not giving one thought to the real facts of marriage.}}
## {{lb|en|intransitive}}
### ''Followed by'' '''[[about#Preposition|about]]''''','' '''[[after#Preposition|after]]''''', or'' '''[[for#Preposition|for]]''': to [[go after]] or [[seek#Verb|seek]] for something, especially [[booty#Noun|booty]] or [[spoils#Noun|spoils]]; to [[maraud]], to plunder; also {{lb|en|generally}}, to [[move#Verb|move]] about [[wildly]] and [[cause#Verb|cause]] [[damage#Noun|damage]]; to [[rampage#Verb|rampage]].
###* {{RQ:Foxe Actes and Monuments|edition=6th|volume=II|chapter=|page=877|column=2|passage=[T]he ſouldiours not yet ſatisfied with ſpoiling and ſacking the reſt that they found in the ſaid Tailleret, raging about the confines thereof, '''rauened''' and made hauocke on euery ſide, of whatſoeuer they could lay hands on, taking priſoners both men and women, which were loden with carriage.}}
###* {{RQ:Girard Cotton Espernon|page=442|passage=[T]he Inhabitants of the Countrey, a barbarous and inhumane people (as generally Sea-borderers are) and inur'd to the ſpoil of VVracks, vvere not over haſty to acquaint the Duke's Officers vvith this, that they might not be diſturbed vvhilst buſie '''ravening''' after Booty.}}
###* {{RQ:Carlyle Friedrich|volume=V|chapter=[[w:Leopold Joseph von Daun|{{quote-gloss|Leopold Joseph von}} Daun]] in Wrestle with Friedrich in the Silesian Hills|pages=92–93|pageref=92|passage=A scandal to be seen, how his Croats and loose hordes went openly '''ravening''' about, bent on mere housebreaking, street-robbery and insolent violence.}}
### To eat greedily; also, ''followed by'' '''[[on#Preposition|on]]''' ''or'' '''[[upon]]''': of an [[animal#Noun|animal]]: to [[prey on]].
###* {{RQ:Elyot Preservative|sig=&#91;B.vi.&#93;|page=31|passage=The couaitous deſyre of riche men is euer vnſaciable. It always '''raueneth''' and neuer is ſatisfied.}}
###* {{quote-book|en|year=1657|author=w:Longus|chapter=The Fourth Book|translator=w:George Thornley|title=[[w:Daphnis and Chloe|Daphnis & Chloe{{nb...|By Longus: Translated out of the Greek by George Thornley Anno 1657}}]]|location=&#91;{{lg|S.l}}&#93;|publisher=&#91;{{lg|s.n.}}&#93;|year_published=1920s?|page=154|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/daphnischloetran00longuoft/page/154/mode/1up|oclc=697712161|passage=For he {{quote-gloss|Daphnis}} had doubled the number {{quote-gloss|of goats}} he had received of Lamo, nor had the Wolf '''raven'd''' away so much as one, and they were all more twaddling fat then the very sheep.}}
###* {{RQ:Somerville Ross Real Charlotte|volume=I|chapter=XII|page=168|passage=[T]he outdoor dogs {{...}} were permitted to '''raven''' unchecked upon chicken bones, fat slices of ham, and luscious leavings of cream when the packing-up time came.}}
###* {{RQ:Dunsany Pegana|chapter=The Bird of Doom and the End|page=93|passage=And the hound Time, when all the Worlds and cities are swept away whereon he used to '''raven''', having no more to devour, shall suddenly die.|footer=A figurative use.}}
###* {{RQ:Wodehouse Code|page=177|passage=I refer to the danger of keeping a dog of this nature and disposition in a bedroom, where it can spring out '''ravening''' on anyone who enters.}}
### ''Sometimes followed by'' '''about''' ''or'' '''on''': to move about [[search#Verb|searching]] for food or prey [[ravenously]].
###* {{RQ:More Apocalypsis|chapter=XIII|page=124|passage=[T]he Arms and Hands of the Bear, {{...}} are his ſtrength and inſtrument of action to '''raven''' and prey vvith; {{...}}}}
### ''Sometimes followed by'' '''after''' ''or'' '''for''': to have a [[ravenous]] [[appetite]] or [[craving#Noun|craving]] for food or prey.
###* {{quote-book|en|year=1587|author=w:Leonard Mascall|chapter=The Nature and Qualities of Hogges, & also the Gouernement thereof|title=The First Booke of Cattell. Wherein is Shewed, the Gouernement of Oxen, Kine, and Calues, and How to Vse Buls and Other Cattell to the Yoke, and Fell.{{nb...|With Diuers Approued Remedies, to Helpe Most Diseases among Cattell: Most Necessary for All, Especially for Husbandmen, Hauing the Gouernement of any such Cattell.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Published by}} [[w:Nicholas Okes|Nicholas Okes]] for Iohn Harison,{{nb...|and are to be sold in Pater Noster Row, at the signe of the White Grayhound.}}|year_published=1610|page=273|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/bim_early-english-books-1475-1640_the-first-booke-of-catte_mascall-leonard_1610/page/275/mode/1up|oclc=228716450|passage=[B]ecause hogs are commonly '''rauening''' for their meat, more then other cattel, it is meet therefore to haue them ringed, or elſe they will doe much hurt in digging and turning vp corne fieldes, {{...}}}}
###* {{RQ:Gaskell Lizzie Leigh|page=115|passage=They passed along towards the great hall-door, where the winds howled and '''ravened''' for their prey; {{...}}|footer=A figurative use.}}
###* {{RQ:Baring-Gould Were-wolves|page=114|passage=The Greek were-wolf is closely related to the vampire. The lycanthropist falls into a cataleptic trance, during which his soul leaves his body, enters that of a wolf and '''ravens''' for blood.}}
### ''Originally followed by'' '''[[with#Preposition|with]]''': to [[experience#Verb|experience]] [[great#Adjective|great]] [[hunger#Noun|hunger]]; to be ravenous.
###* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy|chapter=To the Reader|page=41|passage=For hovv {{...}} ſhall I knovv thee to be a man, vvhen thou kickeſt like an aſſe, neygheſt like an Horſe after vvomen, raueſt in luſt like a Bull, '''raueneſt''' like a Beare, ſtingeſt like a Scorpion, rakeſt like a VVolfe, as ſuttle as a Foxe, as impudent as a Dogge; ſhall I ſay thou art man that haſt all the Symptomes of a beaſt?}}
### {{lb|en|figurative}} To [[take#Verb|take]] and [[exploit#Verb|exploit]] or [[make use]] of greedily.
### {{lb|en|figurative}} ''Sometimes followed by'' '''after''' ''or'' '''for''': to have a [[strong#Adjective|strong]] craving or [[desire#Noun|desire]] for, or to [[do#Verb|do]], something; to [[crave#Verb|crave]], to [[desire#Verb|desire]], to [[yearn#Verb|yearn]].
###* {{RQ:Baring-Gould Roar of the Sea|volume=II|chapter=Jamie's Ride|page=33|passage=Here's my brother thirsting, '''ravening''' to make your acquaintance—and by George! you are in luck's way, young hopeful, to make his.}}
###* {{quote-book|en|year=1931|month=August|author=[[w:J. B. Fagan|James B[ernard] Fagan]]|chapter=[[w:The Improper Duchess (play)|The Improper Duchess]]|title=Famous Plays of 1931|location=London|publisher=[[w:Victor Gollancz Ltd|Victor Gollancz]]{{nb...|Ltd, 14 Henrietta Street, Covent Garden}}|year_published=February 1932|section=Act III|page=237|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.504111/page/n239/mode/1up|oclc=827670712|passage=Take your conscience—what is the choice? On one side the great temple where you can gather the good harvest—on the other a dirty little scandal that you’ve nosed out to fling to paper scavengers who feed it to their readin' millions '''ravening''' for pornographic dirt.}}

