===Etymology===
From {{der|en|la|-}} {{compound|la|floccus|t1=a wisp|naucum|t2=a trifle|nihilum|t3=nothing|pilus|t4=a hair|nocat=1}} + {{af|en|-fication}}.

A jocular coinage, apparently by pupils at {{w|Eton College}},<ref>{{cite-journal|title=Mind your language |author=Dot Wordsworth |magazine={{w|The Spectator}}|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200613003918/https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/mind-your-language-11-june-2011|location=London|publisher={{w|Press Holdings}}|date=11 June 2011|issn=0038-6952|oclc=1766325}}</ref> combining a number of Latin word stems. The word was inspired by a line present in various editions of [[w:William Lily (grammarian)|William Lily's]] (c. 1468–1522) Latin grammars published around the 17th–19th centuries (including the ''Eton Latin Grammar''),<ref>{{cite-book|en|author=R. R. [''i.e.'', Ralph Robinson?]|title=An Engliſh Grammar: Or, A plain Expoſition of Lilie's Grammar|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} Felix Kyngston{{nb...}}|year=1641|page=107|pageurl=https://books.google.ca/books?id=2PZmAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA107|passage=''Flocci'', of a locke of Wooll: ''Nauci'', of a Nut-ſhell: ''Nihili'', of nothing: ''Pili'', of an haire: ''Aſſis'', of a farthing: ''Hujus'', of thus much: ''Teruncii'', of thꝛee ounces, are peculiarly uſed with theſe Verbes: ''Æstimo'', I weigh: ''Pendo'', I make reckoning of: ''Facio'', I make: as, ''Ego illum flocci pendo'': I eſteeme him as naught. ''Nec hujus facio, qui me pili æſtimat'': neither doe I regard him thus much, who eſteemes me as an haire.}}{{cite-book|en|author=William Haine|title=Lilies Rules Construed,{{nb...|Whereunto are added Tho. Robinsons Heteroclites, The Latin Syntaxis, and Qui nihi.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} Roger Norton,{{nb...}}|year=1659|page=54|pageurl=https://books.google.ca/books?id=uosnrGdnIZsC&pg=PA54|column=1|passage=Flocci ''of a lock of wool'', nauci ''of a nut ſhell or pill'', nihili ''nothing'', pili ''of an hair'', aſſis ''of a farthing'', hujus ''thus much'', teruncii ''of three ounces'', peculiaritur{{sic}} ''properly'' adjiciuntur ''are put'' hic verbis ''to theſe verbs'', æſtimo ''I eſteem'', pendo ''I weigh'', facio ''I make reckoning of:'' ut ''as'', Ego pendo ''I eſteem'' illum ''him'' flocci ''as nought:'' Nec ''neither'' facio ''do I regard him'' hujus ''thus much'' qui ''who'' æſtimat ''esteems'' me ''me'' pili ''as an hair''.}}{{cite-book|author=T. W. C. Edwards|chapter=Syntaxis, or the Rules of Grammar Construed|title=The Eton College Grammar: A Plain and Concise Introduction to the Latin Language, being Lily's Grammar Abridged,{{nb...|For the Use of the Young Gentlemen of Eton College: But with the Addition of Many Useful Notes and Observations, and Also of the Accents and Quantity.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} [[w:Simpkin & Marshall|W[illiam] Simpkin and R[ichard] Marshall]],{{nb...}}|year=1826|pages=269–270|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/etonlatingramma02collgoog/page/n283/mode/1up|passage=Flócci ''of a lock of wool'', náuci ''of a nut-shell'', níhili ''of nóthing'', píli ''of a hair'', ássis ''of a pénny'', hújus ''of this'', terúncii ''of a fárthing'', addúntur ''are ádded'', peculiáritèr ''pecúliarly or véry próperly'' vérbis ''to verbs'' æstimándi ''of esteéming:''—ut ''as'', égo péndo íllum ''I válue him'' flócci ''a straw'', nèc fácio ''nor do I regárd him'' hújus ''this'', (viz. ''a snap of the finger and thumb'',) qui ''who'' æstimat me'' esteéms me'' píli (''not'') ''a hair''.}}</ref> in which some nouns commonly used in the [[genitive]] case with some verbs like {{m|la|pendo}} and {{m|la|facio}} are listed, which express evaluating something as worthless or as previously mentioned; see the reference.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˌflɒksɪˌnɔːsɪˌnɪhɪlɪˌpɪlɪfɪˈkeɪʃn/|/ˌflɒksɪˌnɔːkɪˌnɪhɪlɪˌpɪlɪfɪˈkeɪʃn/|a=RP}}
** {{audio|en|en-uk-floccinaucinihilipilification-2.ogg|a=UK}}
* {{IPA|en|/ˌflɒksɪˌnɑsɪˌn(a)ɪhɪlɪˌpɪlɪfɪˈkeɪʃən/|a=GA}}
** {{audio|en|en-us-floccinaucinihilipilification.ogg|a=US}}
{{attention|en|Neither audio pronunciation matches either IPA pronunciation. There would appear to be four logical combinations using either "nɒsɪ" vs "nɔːsɪ" in one position and "nɪ" vs "naɪ" immediately following. The IPA gives only two of the four possibilities and the audio gives only the other two of the four possibilities.}}
* {{hyph|en| flocci|nauci|ni|hili|pili|fi|ca|tion}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|often|humorous}} The act or habit of describing or regarding something as [[unimportant]], of having no value or being [[worthless]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1741|author=w:William Shenstone|title=Letters|passage=I loved him for nothing so much as his '''flocci-nauci-nihili-pili-fication''' of money.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1970|author=w:Patrick O'Brian|title=Master and Commander|passage=There is a systematic '''flocci-nauci-nihili-pilification''' of all other aspects of existence that angers me.}}
#* {{quote-hansard|en|date=10 April 1992|speaker=w:Robert Byrd|report={{w|Congressional Record}}{{nb...|Proceedings and Debates of the 102d Congress, Second Session}}|volume=138, part 7|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|United States Government Printing Office]]|page=9280|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sim_congressional-record-proceedings-and-debates_april-09-30-1992_138-redacted/page/9280/mode/1up|column=3|issn=0363-7239|oclc=13530005|passage=Let me toss an oxymoronic morsel onto the stage of discussion right at this point—to use one of {{w|Jackie Gleason}}’s phrases, “how sweet it is” that, at last, we seem at last to be getting away from the splendiferous '''floccinaucinihilipilifications''', in which we have engaged during these last several days.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Raymond J. Chambers|title=Logic, Law, and Ethics|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Ei03tgPKEKcC&lpg=PA28&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage='''Floccinaucinihilipilification''' in accounting - does it matter?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Sol Steinmetz|title=The life of language|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=raN6AAAAIAAJ&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dS8BU4bIMcTWyQHf94GwDw&ved=0CKsBEOgBMBc4PA|passage=They must be taken with an air of contempt, a '''floccinaucinihilipilification''' of all that can gratify the outward man.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|author=Judith Orloff|title=Emotional Freedom|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_V53VntvlmQC&lpg=PA312&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PA312#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage=Some people with low self-esteem are prone to '''floccinaucinihilipilification''', the habit of deeming everything worthless.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Bruce Ratner|title=Statistical and Machine-Learning Data Mining|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I3KZCfmhWJwC&lpg=PT42&dq=floccinaucinihilipilification&pg=PT42#v=onepage&q=floccinaucinihilipilification&f=false|passage=The quasi statistician would doubtlessly not know how to check this supposition, thus rendering the interpretation of the mean profit as '''floccinaucinihilipilification'''.}}
#* {{quote-hansard|en|speaker=w:Jacob Rees-Mogg|url=http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201212/cmhansrd/cm120221/debtext/120221-0002.htm#12022155000158|date=21 February 2012|column=787|passage=Let me indulge in the '''floccinaucinihilipilification''' of EU judges and quote from the book of Amos about them.}}

