====Verb====
{{en-verb|~|-|might|-}}<!-- |-,mought<l:obsolete> [causes an error; not clear it should be here at all] -->

# {{lb|en|obsolete|intransitive}} To be [[strong]]; to have power (over). {{defdate|8th–17th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|auxiliary}} To [[be able]]; [[can]]. {{defdate|8th–17th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy|edition=2nd|part=II|section=3|member=6|passage=But many times{{...}}we give way to passions we '''may''' resist and will not.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|poetic}} To be able to [[go]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1600|author=w:William Shakespeare|title=w:A Midsummer Night's Dream|section=III.3|passage=O weary night, O long and tedious night, <br> Abate thy houres, shine comforts from the East, <br> That I '''may''' backe to Athens by day-light&nbsp;[…].}}
# {{senseid|en|permission}} {{lb|en|modal auxiliary verb|defective}} To have [[permission]] to, be [[allowed]]. {{ng|Used in granting permission and in questions to make polite requests.}} {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
#: {{syn|en|can|could|might}}
#: {{ux|en|you '''may''' smoke outside}}
#: {{ux|en|'''may''' I sit there?}}
# {{senseid|en|admissibility of a supposition}} {{lb|en|modal auxiliary verb|defective}} {{ng|[[grant#Verb|Granting]] the [[admissibility]] of a [[supposition]], in a way that can be semantically either {{glossary|subjunctive}} or {{glossary|indicative}}<!--even if one asserts that morphosyntactically it signals subjunctivity-->.}}
## {{senseid|en|admissibility of a supposition, conveying possibility}} {{lb|en|modal auxiliary verb|defective}} {{ng|Expressing a present [[possibility]]; [[possibly]]}}. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
##: {{syn|en|could|might<id:admissibility of a supposition, conveying possibility>}}
##: {{ux|en|he '''may''' be lying}}
##: {{ux|en|Schrödinger's cat '''may''' or '''may not''' be in the box.}}
##: {{ux|en| Sam '''may''' be [[intelligent]], but he isn't [[wise]]. [This speaker does not know with certainty whether Sam is intelligent, but the speaker allows the possibility.]}}
##: {{ux|en|A female crocodile '''may''' lay up to forty eggs. [Typical occurrence.]}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|date=October 1, 2011|author=Phil Dawkes|work=BBC Sport
|title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/15045630.stm Sunderland 2-2 West Brom]
|passage=The result '''may''' not quite give the Wearsiders a sweet ending to what has been a sour week, following allegations of sexual assault and drug possession against defender Titus Bramble, but it does at least demonstrate that their spirit remains strong in the face of adversity.}}
## {{senseid|en|admissibility of a supposition, conveying disjunctive or contrastive relation between indicative statements}} {{lb|en|modal auxiliary verb|defective}} {{ng|Expressing a [[disjunctive#English:_grammar, concerning conjunctions|disjunctive]] or [[contrastive#Adjective|contrastive]] relation between {{glossary|indicative}} statements.}}
##: {{syn|en|might<id:admissibility of a supposition, conveying disjunctive or contrastive relation between indicative statements>}}
##: {{ux|en|You '''may''' be my boss, but that doesn't mean you can insult me.}}
##: {{ux|en|A: Sigh. I'm bummed that Stephen Hawking died. B: Well, he '''may''' have died, but he's still alive in our hearts. [This speaker does not doubt that Stephen has died; nonetheless, the verb inflection is not different.]}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-07-06|volume=408|issue=8843|page=68|magazine=w:The Economist
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21580518-terrible-name-interesting-trend-rise-smart-beta The rise of smart beta]
|passage=Investors face a quandary. Cash offers a return of virtually zero in many developed countries; government-bond yields '''may''' have risen in recent weeks but they are still unattractive. Equities have suffered two big bear markets since 2000 and are wobbling again. It is hardly surprising that pension funds, insurers and endowments are searching for new sources of return.}}
# {{lb|en|subjunctive present|defective|chiefly|poetic}} {{ng|Expressing a [[wish#Noun|wish]] (with present subjunctive effect)}}. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: {{syn|en|might}}
#: {{ux|en|'''may''' you win;&emsp; '''may''' the weather be sunny;&emsp; long '''may''' your reign last}}
#: {{ux|en|Let us pray that peace '''may''' soon return to our war-torn homeland.}}
#* {{quote-song|en|year=1974|author=w:Bob Dylan|title=[[w:Forever Young (Bob Dylan song)|Forever Young]]|passage='''May''' God bless and keep you always&nbsp;/ '''May''' your wishes all come true&nbsp;/ '''May''' you always do for others&nbsp;/ And let others do for you&nbsp;/ '''May''' you build a ladder to the stars&nbsp;/ And climb on every rung&nbsp;/ '''May''' you stay forever young|album=Planet Waves}}
#* {{quote-song|en|lyricist=|composer=|title=w:No More Lonely Nights|url=|album=|artist=w:Paul McCartney|year=1984|passage='''May''' I never miss the thrill of being near you}}
# {{lb|en|modal auxiliary verb|defective}} {{n-g|Used in [[modesty]], [[courtesy]], or [[concession]], or to [[soften]] a question or remark.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1744|author=w:Matthew Prior|title=Joe Miller's Jests|origyear=1720|chapter=Phillis's age|edition=7th|passage=How old '''may''' Phillis be, you ask, / Whose Beauty thus all Hearts engages.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MEfD2Lw6ejYC&pg=PA185}}

=====Usage notes=====
* {{m|en||May}} is now a [[defective verb]]. It has no infinitive, no past participle, and no future tense. Forms of {{m|en|to be allowed to}} are used to replace these missing tenses.
* The simple past (both indicative and subjunctive) of {{m|en|may}} is {{m|en|might}}.
* The present tense is negated as {{m|en|[[may]] [[not]]}}, which can be contracted to {{m|en|mayn't}}, although this is old-fashioned; the simple past is negated as {{m|en|[[might]] [[not]]}}, which can be contracted to {{m|en|mightn't}}.
* {{m|en|may|May}} has archaic second-person singular present forms {{m|en|mayest}} and {{m|en|mayst}}.
* Usage of this word in the sense of {{m|en|possibly}} is considered incorrect by some speakers and writers, as it blurs the meaning of the word in the sense ''have permission to''. These speakers and writers prefer to use the word {{m|en|might}} instead.
* Conversely, since '''may not''' is particularly likely to promote confusion between the senses of "will possibly not" and "is forbidden to," some rules for the drafting of laws and regulations proscribe "may not" and require the use of "must not" or similar for clarity. Example: [https://www.justice.gc.ca/eng/rp-pr/csj-sjc/legis-redact/legistics/p1p8.html]
* Wishes are often cast in the imperative rather than the subjunctive mood, not using the word {{m|en||may}}, as in ''Have a great day!'' rather than ''May you have a great day''. The use of '''may''' for this purpose may lend a more formal, literary, or solemn feeling (perhaps jocularly so) to the wish. Moreover, wishes in the subjunctive need not use ''may'' if the meaning is clear without it, which is the case mainly for established expressions in the third-person singular such as {{m|en|God help someone|God help you}}.

