===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂ewg-}} {{dercat|en|itc-pro|ine-pro}}
From {{der|en|fr|auguste||noble, stately; august}} or {{der|en|la|augustus||majestic, venerable, august; imperial, royal}},<ref>{{R:Lexico}}</ref> from {{m|la|augeō||to augment, increase; to enlarge, expand, spread}}. {{doublet|en|Augustus}}.

====Adjective====
{{en-adj|er,more}}

# [[awe-inspiring|Awe-inspiring]], [[majestic]], [[noble]], [[venerable]].
#: {{co|en|an '''august''' patron of the arts}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Gilbert Bishop of Sarum [''i.e.'', {{w|Gilbert Burnet}}]|chapter=Article VII. Of the Old Testament.|title=An Exposition of the XXXIX Articles of the Church of England|location=Oxford|publisher=At the [[w:Oxford University Press|Clarendon Press]]|year=1796|page=123|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZygPAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA123|oclc=191672588|passage=In the [[w:Psalms|book of Pſalms]] there are many things ſaid of {{w|David}}, which ſeem capable of a much '''auguſter''' ſenſe than can be pretended to be anſwered by any thing that befel himſelf.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=William Sollis|title=A Sermon, Preached in Holsworthy Church on Thursday, August 31, 1837, at the Anniversaries of the Societies for Promoting Christian Knowledge, and for Propagating the Gospel in Foreign Parts.{{nb...|Published by Request of the Members then Present.}}|location=Launceston, Cornwall|publisher=Penheale-Press, Rev. H. A. Simcoe|date=31 August 1837|page=7|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LedoAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA7|oclc=31888331|passage=[W]e shall not, I think, be able to find language which can convey in few words more fully the idea we should always have impressed on our minds of the '''august''' character of our Lord, than the expression, "the word of life."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Elijah Coleman Bridgman|E[lijah] C[oleman] Bridgman]]|chapter=Governmental Affairs|title=A Chinese Chrestomathy in the Canton Dialect|location=Macao|publisher=[[w:Samuel Wells Williams|S[amuel] Wells Williams]]|year=1841|section=section second (Imperial Titles)|page=558|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl9cAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA558|oclc=806406066|passage=The commands of the '''august''' sovereign are the imperial commands, or the phœnix (the incomparable) mandate.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Robert Browning|chapter=Luria|title=Bells and Pomegranates|location=London|publisher=w:Edward Moxon|year=1846|volume=VIII (Luria; and A Soul’s Tragedy)|oclc=793033490|newversion=republished in|title2=Poems [...] In Two Volumes|edition2=new|location2=London|publisher2={{w|Chapman & Hall}},{{nb...|186, Strand}}|year2=1849|volume2=II|section2=act IV|page2=192|pageurl2=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.hwekxw;view=1up;seq=204|oclc2=1145736|passage=—Inconsciously to the '''augustest''' end / Thou hast arisen: second not in rank / So much as time, to him who first ordained / That Florence, thou art to destroy, should be— {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Sei Shōnagon|chapter=[[w:The Pillow Book|Makura Zōshi]] [The Attack of the Dog Okinamaro upon the Cat Miyōbu no Otodo]|mainauthor=[[w:William George Aston|W[illiam] G[eorge] Aston]]|title=A History of Japanese Literature|location=London|publisher=[[w:Heinemann (publisher)|William Heinemann]]|year=1899|page=111|pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/historyofjapanes00astouoft#page/111/mode/1up|oclc=912202873|passage=The foolish dog {{...}} flew at the cat, who in her fright and consternation took refuge behind the screen of the breakfast-room where his Majesty then was. The Mikado was greatly shocked and agitated. He took the cat into his '''august''' bosom, and summoning the chamberlain Tadataka, gave orders that Okinamaro should have a good thrashing and be banished to Dog Island at once.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Alan Smith|title=[[w:Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] back on top as Riyad Mahrez hat-trick downs [[w:Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/05/swansea-city-leicester-city-premier-league-match-report|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329152800/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/05/swansea-city-leicester-city-premier-league-match-report|archivedate=29 March 2017|newspaper=w:The Guardian|location=London|date=5 December 2015|passage=For once the story was not about {{w|Jamie Vardy}}, unable to equal {{w|Jimmy Dunne}}'s top-flight record of scoring in a dozen consecutive games, but about his '''august''' deputy {{w|Riyad Mahrez}}.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2016|author=w:Liu Cixin|translator=w:Ken Liu|title=w:Death's End|publisher=Tor|isbn=978-0-7653-8663-2|original={{w|三体III：死神永生|死神永生|lang=zh}}|page=280|text=Countless proposals flooded in, sent by sources as '''august''' as the World Academy of Sciences and as humble as elementary schools.}}
# Of noble [[birth]].
#: {{co|en|an '''august''' lineage}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Walter Fitz Patrick|chapter=I|title=The Great [[w:Louis, Prince of Condé (1530–1569)|Condé]] and the Period of the Fronde: A Historical Sketch|location=London|publisher=[[w:Thomas Cautley Newby|T[homas] Cautley Newby]], publisher,{{nb...|30, Welbeck Street, Cavendish Square.}}|year=1873|volume=I|page=7|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=yiQtAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA7|oclc=3251659|passage=A branch of the house of Lorraine, in comparison with which even the royal race of Capet was mean, the Guises traced back their '''august''' lineage through a long line of warrior princes to the Imperial figure of {{w|Charlemagne}}.}}

