==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-|*preyH-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Friday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|frīġedæġ}}. Compound of {{m|ang|Frīġ}} and {{m|ang|dæġ|t=day}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*Frījā dag}}, a calque of {{der|en|la|diēs Veneris}}, via an association ({{m|la|interpretātiō germānica}}) of the goddess [[Frigg]] with the Roman goddess of love [[Venus]]. See also [[friend]].

Compare {{cog|fy|freed}}, {{cog|nds-de|Freedag}}, {{m|nds-de|Friedag}}, {{cog|nl|vrijdag}}, {{cog|de|Freitag}}, {{cog|da|fredag}}.
{{cog|non|Frigg}} (genitive {{m|non|Friggjar}}), {{cog|osx|Fri}}, and {{cog|ang|Frīġ}} are derived from {{cog|gem-pro|*Frijjō}}. Frigg is cognate with {{cog|sa|प्रिया|tr=priyā́|t=wife}}. The root also appears in {{cog|osx|fri|t=beloved lady}}; in {{cog|sv|fria}}, in {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|no|-}} as {{m|da|fri|t=to propose for marriage}}; a related meaning exists in Icelandic as {{m|is|frjá|t=to love}} and similarly in {{cog|nl|vrijen|t=to make love (to have sex)}}.

Compare Japanese [[金曜日]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|frīʹdā|frīʹdē|a=RP,GA}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈfɹaɪ.deɪ/|/-.di/}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-Friday.ogg|a=RP}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-Friday.ogg|a=GA}}
* {{IPA|en|/ˈfɹaɪ.də/|a=Northumbria}}
* {{hyphenation|en|Fri|day}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪdeɪ|aɪdi|s=2}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|Q130}}The sixth day of the [[week]] in many religious traditions, and the fifth day of the week in systems using the [[w:ISO 8601|ISO 8601]] norm; the [[Muslim]] [[Sabbath]]; it follows [[Thursday]] and precedes [[Saturday]].
#: {{syn|en|Sixth Day|q=Quakerism}}
#* {{quote-web|en|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201029114129/https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2019/09/11/first-time-years-full-moon-will-occur-this-friday-th/|work=w:The Washington Post|passage=For a micromoon and '''Friday''' the 13th full moon to occur together is extraordinarily rare. The last time it happened was in 1832 and it won't happen again for more than 500 years according to Tony Rice, a meteorologist and engineer at NASA.|title=For the first time in 13 years, a full moon rises this Friday the 13th|date=2019-09-13|author=Matthew Cappucci}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2020-03-30|author=T.W. Lewis|title=Solid Ground: A Foundation For Winning In Work and In Life|publisher=T.W. Lewis |isbn=9780960095308
|text=Their mindset is the grindset, and they love the grind. I used to have a sales manager who didn't think this way. On '''Fridays''', he'd always say, “Happy '''Friday'''.” A lot of people feel that way, but I never liked that phrase because it{{nb...}}}}
<!--probably just an attributive form of the noun: #An appointment, person (like Man Friday in ''Robinson Crusoe''), or feeling associated with this day of the week.-->
# {{lb|en|colloquial, with possessive}} The last [[workday]] in a work schedule that is not Monday through Friday.
#: {{ux|en|Tomorrow's Thursday, but I have Friday and Saturday off, so really it's my '''Friday'''.}}

