===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Sonday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|sunnandæġ}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*Sunnōn dag|lit=day of the Sun}}, equivalent to {{compound|en|sun|day}}, as a {{glossary|calque}} ({{m|la|interpretātiō germānica}}) of {{der|en|la|diēs Sōlis}}; declared the "venerable day of the sun" by Roman Emperor [[w:Constantine the Great|Constantine]] on March 7, 321 {{C.E.}}

Compare {{cog|stq|Sundai||Sunday}}, {{cog|nds-de|Sünndag}}, {{cog|nl|zondag}}, {{cog|fy|snein}}, {{cog|de|Sonntag}}, {{cog|da|søndag}}.

