===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|Q132}}The first day of the [[week]] in many religious traditions, and the seventh day of the week in systems using the [[w:ISO 8601|ISO 8601]] standard; the [[Christian]] [[Sabbath]]; the [[Lord's Day]]; it follows [[Saturday]] and precedes [[Monday]].
#: {{syn|en|First Day|q=Quakerism}}
#* {{quote-song|en|year=1988|author=w:Morrissey|album=w:Viva Hate|title=w:Everyday Is Like Sunday|passage=Every day is like '''Sunday''' / Every day is silent and grey}}
#* {{quote-journal
|en
|date=2012-06-19
|author=Phil McNulty
|title=England 1-0 Ukraine
|work=w:BBC Sport
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18181971
|page=
|passage=And after missing a simple header in the first half, the Manchester United striker ensured England topped Group D to set up a quarter-final meeting with Italy in Kiev on '''Sunday'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Daniel Burke|title=How Pete Buttigieg found God|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/16/politics/pete-buttigieg-religious-journey|date=2019-08-16|passage=But on that '''Sunday''' it was filled with Episcopalians from around the country who had traveled to South Bend to attend his campaign launch.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20211022035759/https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/16/politics/pete-buttigieg-religious-journey/}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[newspaper]] published on Sunday.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1974|author=John le Carré|title=Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy|passage=I gave him the switchboard with my love, went down to the Savoy for breakfast and read the '''Sundays'''.}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[comic strip]] published in a Sunday newspaper.
#* {{quote-text|en|year=2017|author=Mark Arnold|title=Pocket Full of Dennis the Menace
|passage=It just wasn't his thing, although he did beautiful '''Sundays''' for however long he did them. So as soon as he could, he hired someone to do the '''Sundays'''. Karen and I would do some dailies, but we were the Sunday artists.}}
# {{lb|en|informal|attributive}} {{n-g|Describes someone who does something occasionally or casually, and therefore without skill.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2010-11-09|author=Rosemary Wells|title=On the Blue Comet|publisher=Candlewick Press|isbn=9780763654191|page=113
|text=Your face is the color of a '''Sunday''' swimmer who swallowed half the pool.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2010-03-30|author=Lance Armstrong|title=Every Second Counts|publisher=Random House|isbn=9781407064079|page=51
|text=My limbs felt hollow, empty. Empty, empty, empty. A '''Sunday''' cyclist on a casual ride could have passed me.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2010-12-15|author=Peter Everett|title=Matisse's War|publisher=Random House|isbn=9781446412206
|text=Below, a '''Sunday''' painter dabs at a canvas near the Pont Neuf, his suit as natty as any Landru wore. He tilts his bowler hat and steps back to view his efforts. 'What is a '''Sunday''' painter?' Matisse says aloud. 'When we start, we are all '''Sunday''' painters.'}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2016-01-18|author=Renars Sidrabs|title=Memoirs of a Drunk|publisher=Xlibris Corporation|isbn=9781514447765|text=If he even tries it, then his addiction will take over again. An alcoholic can never become a “'''Sunday''' drinker”.}}
# {{lb|en|informal|attributive}} {{n-g|Describes something particularly [[fine]] and [[elegant]], particularly something that could be worn to or used at [[church]].}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|author=Emanuel Zeylmans|title=Willem Zeylmans Van Emmichoven: An Inspiration for Anthroposophy : a Biography|publisher=Temple Lodge Publishing|isbn=9781902636351|page=9
|text=His father replies with a special tone of voice (his {{'}}'''Sunday''' voice', which he also used for reading fairy tales): 'That is about the tragedy of human beings!'}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Marion Houldsworth|title=The Morning Side of the Hill|publisher=Boolarong Press|isbn=9781921555473|page=150
|text=It landed on the wire mesh in front of me, thrust its thin, monkey-arm through the wire, seized my '''Sunday''' hat, blue satin ribbons, rosettes and all, and squealing in triumph made off with it, leaping and bounding, to the top of the monkey-tree.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2011-04-29|author=Tommy Chamberlain|title=A Spoon Full of Sugar|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=9781462001408|page=6
|text=On the day of the show I decided to wear my good blue '''Sunday''' suit, even though Ms. Arnoldi had prescribed flannel shirts, boots, and jeans for all the boys.}}

