===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|fr|antonyme}} (1840s and 1850s), which was modeled on earlier {{m|fr|synonyme}} and influenced by the [[etymon#Noun|etymons]] of {{der|en|grc|ἀντωνυμία||pronoun}}; credit for popularization of the French loanword's [[naturalize#English:_linguistics|naturalization]] into English is given principally to Charles John Smith and his 1867 book ''Synonyms and Antonyms: Or, Kindred Words and Their Opposites. Collected and Contrasted.''<ref name="Smith-1867">{{cite-book |en |author=Charles John Smith |origyear=1867 |year=1868 |title=Synonyms and Antonyms: Or, Kindred Words and Their Opposites. Collected and Contrasted |edition=2nd |publisher=Bell and Daldy |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=plQIAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> {{surf|en|ant-|-onym}}.

