===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|Q131779}} {{lb|en|semantics}} A word which has the [[opposite]] meaning of another word.
#: {{syn|en|counterterm|opposite}}
#: {{ant|en|synonym}}
#: {{cot|en
|near-antonym|;
|coordinate term|cohyponym|;<!--fellow type of the same larger class, but not diametrically opposite-->
|antiphrasis|;<!--intentionally discrepant meaning-->
|near-synonym|parasynonym|plesionym|;<!--nearly the same-->
}}
#: {{ux|en|“Rich” is an '''antonym''' of “poor”; “full” is an '''antonym''' of “empty”.}}
## A word that describes one end of a scale, while its opposite describes the other end, such as ''large'' versus ''small''; a {{l|en|gradable antonym}}.
##* {{quote-book|en|year=2005|author=Andrew John Merrison; Aileen Bloomer; Patrick Griffiths; Christopher J. Hall|title=Introducing Language in Use|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/introducing-language-in-use-a-coursebook/oclc/705997377|page=111|text=All four lines of the pattern are required to establish that ''hot'' and ''cold'' are '''antonyms'''. <br/>''The water is hot'' entails ''The water is not cold''. <br/>''The water is cold'' entails ''The water is not hot''.<br/>''The water is not hot'' does not entail ''The water is cold''. <br/>''The water is not cold'' does not entail ''The water is hot''.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|author=Chris Baltimore|title=FEATURE-Oil dollars help Houston dodge U.S. economic woes|magazine=w:Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/legal/government/feature-oil-dollars-help-houston-dodge-u-s-economic-woes-idUSN29389418/|date=2008-10-14|passage="The word 'boom' always makes me uneasy because the '''antonym''' of it is bust," said Patrick Jankowski, vice president of research at the Greater Houston Partnership. "Houston is not in a boom -- it is on a new path."}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|author=Isabelle Yr Carlsson|title=Denmark shuts down cannabis street in Christiania hippie enclave|magazine=w:Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/denmark-shuts-down-cannabis-street-christiania-hippie-enclave-2024-04-06/|date=2024-04-06|passage="To me, Pusher Street is actually the least unique, right? It is what I associate with violence, gangs, murder, threats, and everything which are actually '''antonyms''' to what Christiania is," said Mathilde Brandstrup, a Christiania local.}}

