* {{rhymes|en|eɪʃən|s=4}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of [[denoting]], or something (such as a [[symbol]]) that [[denote]]s
# {{lb|en|logic|linguistics|semiotics}} The [[primary]], [[surface]], [[literal]], or [[explicit]] [[meaning]] of a [[signifier]] such as a [[word]], [[phrase]], or [[symbol]]; that which a word denotes, as contrasted with its [[connotation]]; the aggregate or set of objects of which a word may be predicated.
#: {{ux|en|The '''denotations''' of the two expressions "the morning star" and "the evening star" are the same (i.e. both expressions denote the planet Venus), but their connotations are different.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2018|author=James Lambert|title=A multitude of ‘lishes’: The nomenclature of hybridity|journal=English World-Wide|page=6|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318367113_A_multitude_of_lishes_The_nomenclature_of_hybridity
|text=Regarding '''denotation''', the terms were generally used to refer to a wide range of language contact varieties and features.}}
# {{lb|en|philosophy|logic}} The [[intension]] and [[extension]] of a word
# {{lb|en|semantics}} Something signified or referred to; a particular meaning of a [[symbol]]
# {{lb|en|computer science}} Any mathematical object which describes the meanings of expressions from the languages, formalized in the theory of [[denotational semantics]]
# {{lb|en|media studies}} A first level of [[analysis]]: what the audience can visually see on a page. Denotation often refers to something [[literal]], and avoids being a [[metaphor]].

