===Etymology===
From {{confix|en|hyp|onym}} or {{confix|en|hypo|nym}}; from {{der|en|grc|ὑπό||under}} + {{m|grc|ὄνυμα}} ("[[appellation]]"), a Doric specific dialectal form of {{m|grc|ὄνομα||name}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈhaɪpəʊ.nɪm/|/ˈhaɪpə.nɪm/|a=UK}}
** {{homophone|en|hypernym}}
* {{IPA|en|/ˈhaɪ.poʊ.nɪm/|/ˈhaɪpə.nɪm/|a=US,Canada}}
* {{audio|en|En-ca-hyponym.ogg|a=Canada}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
{{wp|+y and hypernymy}}

# {{senseid|en|Q680042}} {{lb|en|semantics}} A more [[specific]] {{l|en|term|id=name for a concept}}; a [[subordinate]] grouping word or phrase; a term designating a [[subclass]] of another more general class described by the given word.
#: {{syn|en|subordinate#Noun}}
#: {{ant|en|hypernym|hyperonym|superordinate#Noun}}
#: {{hypo|en|troponym}}
#: {{cot|en|synonym|;|near-synonym|;|meronym|;|cohyponym|;|''more at'' [[Wiktionary:Semantic relations]]}}
#: {{ux|en|The words “dog”, “cat”, and “horse” are '''hyponyms''' of “animal” because dogs, cats, and horses are types of animal.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1977|author=Ruth Kempson|title=Semantic Theory|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0521216133|page=86|passage=''Woman'' itself has as other '''hyponyms''', ''sculptress'' and ''waitress'', but is itself a '''hyponym''' of ''adult''.}}

