==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|fr|sémantique}}, displacing earlier {{m|en|semasiology}}. From {{der|en|grc|σημαντικός}}. {{surf|en|semantic|-ics}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/sɪˈmæntɪks/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-semantics.wav|a=Southern England}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Wodencafe-semantics.wav|a=US}}

===Noun===
{{wp}}
{{en-noun|~|*}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A branch of [[linguistics]] studying the [[meaning]] of words. {{defdate|1893}}
#: {{hol|en|linguistics}}
#: {{mer|en|semasiology|onomasiology}}
#: {{comeronyms|en|pragmatics|phonology|morphology|grammar}}
#: {{coi|en|lexical '''semantics'''}}; &emsp; {{coi|en|cognitive '''semantics'''}}; &emsp; {{coi|en|computational '''semantics'''}}; &emsp; {{coi|en|historical '''semantics'''}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Semantics''' is a foundation of [[lexicography]].}}
# The study of the relationship between words and their meanings.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Patrick Blackburn; Johan Bos; Kristina Striegnitz|url=http://www.learnprolognow.org/lpnpage.php?pagetype=html&pageid=lpn-htmlse32|title=Learn Prolog Now!|section=section 8.1|passage=In fact, nowadays a lot is known about the '''semantics''' of natural languages, and it is surprisingly easy to build semantic representations which partially capture the meaning of sentences or even entire discourses.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328054537/http://www.learnprolognow.org/lpnpage.php?pagetype=html&pageid=lpn-htmlse32|archivedate=28 March 2015}}
# The meaning or set of meanings of a linguistic element, such as a [[word]], [[morpheme]] or [[utterance]].
#: {{ux|en|In very ancient or poorly documented languages, the precise '''semantics''' of words tend to be uncertain.}}
## The meanings of individual words, as opposed to the overall meaning of a passage.
##: {{ux|en|The '''semantics''' of the terms used are debatable.}}
# {{lb|en|computer science}} The meaning of computer language constructs, in contrast to their form or [[syntax]].
#: {{ux|en|file sharing and locking '''semantics'''}}
# {{lb|en|loose|colloquial|of a detail or distinction}} [[pettiness|Pettiness]] or [[triviality]].
#: {{ux|en|Who cares? This is all just '''semantics'''!}}

