===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|grammar|narrowly}} A word that functions as the name of a specific object or set of objects, such as [[person]], [[animal]], [[place]], [[word]], [[thing]], [[phenomenon]], [[substance]], [[quality]], or [[idea]]: one of the basic parts of [[speech]] in many languages, including [[English]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Harry Pearson|title=London 2012 can legacy by verbing the noun|magazine=w:The Guardian|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/24/us/pope-adjectives-intl-hnk-scli|date=2011-09-01|passage=Records have been broken, races have been dedicated, dreams have been dreamed, starts have been falsed and '''nouns''' have been verbed.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240922053101/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/sep/01/sport-language-harry-pearson}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Jessie Yeung|title=Pope Francis loves nouns but is ‘allergic’ to adjectives|magazine=w:CNN|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/sep/01/sport-language-harry-pearson|date=2019-09-24|passage=Communication is a kind of beauty, he said – and “beauty manifests itself from the '''noun''' itself, without strawberries on the cake.”|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927032029/https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/24/us/pope-adjectives-intl-hnk-scli/|quotee=w:Pope Francis}}
# {{lb|en|grammar|now|rare|loosely}} Either a [[word]] that can be used to refer to a [[person]], [[animal]], [[place]], [[thing]], [[phenomenon]], [[substance]], [[quality]] or [[idea]], or a word that modifies or describes a previous word or its referent; a [[substantive]] or [[adjective]], sometimes also including other parts of speech such as [[numeral]] or [[pronoun]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1753|author=Thomas Martin|title=An Explanation of the Accidence and Grammar To the End of the Syntax in which The Grounds of each Rule in the Syntax are laid down in the plainest Manner. Compiled By way of Question and Answer, For the Use of Schools.|location=London|page=1|passage=''Q.'' What is a '''Noun'''? A. The Name of a Thing. Q. How many Sorts of '''Nouns''' are there? [...] ''A.'' A '''Noun''' Substantive, and a '''Noun''' Adjective.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1786|author=Signor Veneroni|title=The Complete Italian Master; Containing The best and easiest Rules for attaining that Language|location=London|page=6|passage=A '''Noun''' is a word which serves to name and distinguish some thing; [...]. There are two sorts of '''nouns'''; one is called a '''noun''' substantive, and the other a '''noun''' adjective.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1852|author=Leonhard Schmitz|title=Elementary Latin grammar|location=Edinburgh|page=123|passage=The first part of a compound word is either a '''noun''' (substantive, adjective, or numeral), an adverb, or a preposition, and in a very few cases a verb.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1856|author=R. G. Latham|title=Logic in its application to language|location=London|page=224|passage=Finally, there are many who limit the parts of speech to the '''noun''', the verb, and the particle; referring to the first, the substantive, the adjective, and the pronoun (including the article), to the second the participle, to the third the remainder.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1956|author=Herbert Weir Smyth; Gordon M. Messing|title=Greek Grammar|location=Cambridge|publisher=Harvard University Press|page=44|chapter=189. Parts of Speech|passage=Greek has the following parts of speech: substantives, adjectives, pronouns, verbs, adverbs, prepositions, conjunctions, and particles. In this Grammar '''''noun''''' is used to include both the substantive and the adjective.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1894|year_published=2008|author=B. L. Gildersleeve; G. Lodge|title=Gildersleeve's Latin Grammar|publisher=Dover|page=9|passage=The Parts of Speech are the '''Noun''' (Substantive and Adjective), the Pronoun, the Verb, and the Particles (Adverb, Preposition, and Conjunction)[.]}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993|author=Arthur Anthony Macdonell|title=A Vedic Grammar For Students|edition=1st Indian|location=Delhi|page=283|passage=The parts of which the sentence may consist are either inflected words: the '''noun''' (substantive and adjective) and the verb, the participle which shares the nature of both, and the pronoun; or uninflected words: prepositions, adverbs, and conjunctions.}}
# {{lb|en|computing}} An [[object]] within a [[user interface]] to which a certain [[action]] or [[transformation]] (i.e., [[verb]]) is applied.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1992|title=Languages for Developing User Interfaces|author=Brad A. Myers; David C. Smith; Bruce Horn|chapter=19|passage='''Nouns''' are the data; verbs are the data transformations, and therefore verbs represent much of the complexity of systems.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|page=59|author=Jeff Raskin|title=The Humane Interface|passage=You choose either (1) the verb (change font) first and then select the '''noun''' (the paragraph) to which the verb should apply or (2) the noun first and then apply the verb.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2005|author=Barbara J. Grosz|journal=Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society|volume=149|issue=4|passage=Thus, in essence, the mouse provides a capability for picking among a set of '''nouns''' (for instance, the file to which to apply some action) and verbs (such as "edit" or "insert")}}

====Usage notes====
* ''(narrow sense)'' In English (and in many other languages), a noun can serve as the subject or object of a [[verb]]. For example, the English words {{m|en|table}} and {{m|en|computer}} are nouns. See [[w:Part of speech|Wikipedia’s article “Parts of speech”]].

