===Etymology 2===
From the verb {{m|en|swap}}. {{etydate|1620}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
[[File:Swapping apples.svg|thumb| [[w:en:Alice and Bob|Alice]] has a red apple and Bob has a green apple. After a '''swap''', Alice has the green apple and Bob has the red apple.]]

# An [[exchange]] of two comparable things.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|author=w:Sir Walter Scott|title=w:Tales of My Landlord|section=The Bride of Lammermoor|passage=I e’en changed it, as occasion served, with the skippers o’ Dutch luggers and French vessels, for gin and brandy{{...}} a gude '''swap''' too, between what cheereth the soul of man and that which dingeth it clean out of his body}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=w:TIME|title=Who Is Cilia Flores? What to Know About Maduro’s Wife Amid Fall of Venezuela's First Couple|date=Jan 5 2026|author=Callum Sutherland
|text=Flores' nephews were each sentenced to 18 years' imprisonment in 2017 for conspiring to import cocaine, but they were released in 2022 by the Biden Administration as part of a prisoner '''swap''' with Venezuela.
|url=https://time.com/7343188/who-is-cilia-flores-maduro-wife-venezuela-politics/}}
# {{lb|en|finance}} A financial [[derivative]] in which two parties agree to exchange one stream of non-normal [[cashflow]] against another stream.
# {{lb|en|computing|informal|uncountable}} Space available in a [[swap file]] for use as [[auxiliary]] [[memory]].
#: {{ux|en|How much '''swap''' do you need?}}
# {{lb|en|Cantab slang}} A social meal at a [[restaurant]] between two [[university]] [[society|societies]], usually involving [[drinking]] and [[banter]]; commonly associated with [[fine|fining]] and [[penny]]ing; equivalent to a [[crewdate]] at {{w|University of Oxford|Oxford University}}.

