====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|nonstandard|colloquial}} To use any word that is or was not a verb (especially a noun) as if it were a verb.
#* a. '''1981''' Feb 22, unknown Guardian editor as quoted by William Safire, ''On Language'', in ''New York Times'', pSM3
#*: Haig, in congressional hearings before his confirmatory, paradoxed his auditioners by abnormalling his responds so that verbs were nouned, nouns '''verbed''' and adjectives adverbised. He techniqued a new way to vocabulary his thoughts so as to informationally uncertain anybody listening about what he had actually implicationed... .
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=January 25 1993|journal=Calvin and Hobbes|author=Bill Watterson
|passage=I like to '''verb''' words.... I take nouns and adjectives and use them as verbs. Remember when "access" was a thing? Now it's something you DO. It got '''verbed'''. '''Verbing''' weirds language.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1997|author=David. F. Griffiths; Desmond J. Higham|title=learning LAT<sub>E</sub>X|page=8
|passage=Nouns should ''never'' be '''verbed'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=Oct 5 2005|author=Jeffrey Mattison|title=Letters|journal=The Christian Science Monitor|page=8
|passage=In English, '''verbing''' nouns is okay}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Harry Pearson|title=London 2012 can legacy by '''verbing''' the noun|magazine=w:The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/sep/01/sport-language-harry-pearson|date=2011-09-01|passage=Records have been broken, races have been dedicated, dreams have been dreamed, starts have been falsed and nouns have been '''verbed'''.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240922053101/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/sep/01/sport-language-harry-pearson}}
# {{lb|en|linguistics|social sciences}} {{n-g|Used as a [[placeholder]] for any verb.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1946|author=Rand Corporation|title=The Rand Paper Series
|passage=''For example, one-part versions of the proposition "The doctor pursued the lawyer" were "The doctor '''verbed''' the object,"'' ...}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1964|title=Journal of Mathematical Psychology
|passage=''Each sentence had the same basic structure: ''The subject transitive '''verbed''' the object who intransitive '''verbed''' in the location''.''}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1998|author=Marilyn A. Walker; Aravind Krishna Joshi|title=Centering Theory in Discourse
|passage=''The sentence frame was ''Dan '''verbed''' Ben approaching the store''. This sentence frame was followed in all cases by ''He went inside''.''}}

