===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|del}}, {{m|enm|dele}}, from {{inh|en|ang|dǣl|t=part, share, portion}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*daili}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*dailiz|t=part, deal}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro||*dʰ(h₁)-oy-lo-|t=part, watershed}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|dele||part, portion}}, {{cog|fy|diel||part, share}}, {{cog|nl|deel||part, share, portion}}, {{cog|de|Teil||part, portion, section}}, {{cog|da,sl,sv|del|t=part}}, {{cog|is|deila||division, contention}}, {{cog|got|𐌳𐌰𐌹𐌻𐍃||portion}}. Related to {{cog|ang|dāl||portion}}. More at [[dole]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|portion}} {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[division]], a [[portion]], a [[share]], a [[part]], a [[piece]].
#: {{syn|en|allotment|apportionment|distribution}}
#: {{ux|en|We gave three '''deals''' of grain in tribute to the king.}}
# {{senseid|en|amount}} {{lb|en|often followed by ''of''}} An [[indefinite]] [[quantity]] or [[amount]]; a [[lot]] (''now usually qualified by'' {{m|en|great}} ''or'' {{m|en|good}}).
#: {{syn|en|batch|flock|good deal|great deal|hatful|heap|load|lot|mass|mess|mickle|mint|muckle|peck|pile|plenty|pot|quite a little|raft|sight|slew|spate|stack|tidy sum|wad|whole lot|whole slew|Thesaurus:lot}}
#* {{RQ:Austen Mansfield Park|chapter=II|volume=I|page=35|passage=There is a vast '''deal''' of difference in memories, as well as in every thing else, and therefore you should make allowance for your cousin, and pity her deficiency.}}
#* {{RQ:Melville Moby-Dick|chapter=32|passage=There is a '''deal''' of obscurity concerning the identity of the species thus multitudinously baptized.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1928|author=Lawrence R. Bourne|chapter=3|title=Well Tackled!|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL5387037W |passage=&ldquo;They know our boats will stand up to their work,&rdquo; said Willison, &ldquo;and that counts for a good '''deal'''. A low estimate from us doesn't mean scamped work, but just that we want to keep the yard busy over a slack time.&rdquo;}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-07|author=David Simpson|volume=188|issue=26|page=36|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly|title=Fantasy of navigation|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/may/18/falling-upwards-richard-holmes-review|passage=Like most human activities, ballooning has sponsored heroes and hucksters and a good '''deal''' in between. For every dedicated scientist patiently recording atmospheric pressure and wind speed while shivering at high altitudes, there is a carnival barker with a bevy of pretty girls willing to dangle from a basket or parachute down to earth.}}

