==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|marchaundise|t=commerce, trading; buying; business transaction, deal; merchandise, goods, wares; possessions}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=marchaundīse|pos=n|id=16587756}}</ref> from {{der|en|xno|marchaundise}} and {{der|en|fro|marcheandise}} (modern {{cog|fr|marchandise}}), from {{der|en|fro|marcheant|t=seller, vendor}} (ultimately from {{der|en|la|mercātus|t=buying and selling, trade, traffic; market; marketplace}}, possibly originally {{der|en|ett|-}}) + {{m|fro|-ise|pos=suffix forming {{glossary|feminine}} nouns, often denoting a quality or state}}. The English word is analysable as {{suffix|en|merchant|ise}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alter|en|merchandize|merchaundise|merchaundize||obsolete}}
* {{alter|en|mdse||abbreviation}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ˈmɜː.t͡ʃənˌdaɪs/|/-daɪz/|a=RP}}
* {{IPA|en|/ˈmɝ.t͡ʃənˌdaɪs/|/-daɪz/|a=GA}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-merchandise.ogg|a=GA}}
* {{hyphenation|en|mer|chan|dise}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[good|Goods]] which are or were offered or intended for sale.
#: {{ux|en|Good business depends on having good '''merchandise'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|act=IV|scene=i|page=84|column=2|passage=So, if a Sonne that is by his Father ſent about '''Merchandize''', doe ſinfully miſcarry vpon the Sea; the imputation of his vvickedneſſe, by your rule, ſhould be impoſed vpon his Father that ſent him: {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1908|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|title=Sessional papers. Inventory control record 1|page=29
|passage=The custom of giving away '''merchandise''' for advertising purposes is greatly on the increase in this country. More goods are now distributed in one year as advertising novelties and as premiums than in a decade 10 or 15 years ago.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1936|author=Cecil Day Lewis|title=The Whispering Roots|publisher=Jonathan Cape|page=175
|passage=It has been stated that Fred Beers is giving free '''merchandise''' to this store and I believe you will find that one of your inspectors obtained a bottle of milk free when he purchased some groceries on Thursday Nov. 23rd [1933].}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Commercial goods connected (branded) with an entity such as a team, band, company, charity, work of fiction, festival, or meme. {{q|Commonly shortened to {{m|en|merch}}.}}
# {{lb|en|countable|archaic}} A commodity offered for sale; an article of [[commerce]]; a kind of merchandise.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Best Merchandise, Or a Cleare Discovery of the Evident Difference, and Admirable Advantage, Between Our Traffike with God for the True Treasure and with Men for Temporall Commodity|page=9|author=John Wing (Minister of the English congregation at Flushing.)|year=1622|passage=Would we then see in what sence heavenly things may be called a '''merchandise''', and in what sence not; this is easy to him that will understand.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Parliamentary Debates from the Year 1803 to the Present Time|author=Great Britain. Parliament|date=June 18, 1822|title=Marriage Act Amendment Bill|year_published=1823|page=1135|passage=What security was there that she might not be a very unfit person, one who had made a '''merchandise''' of her charms, the child itself being the offspring of some accidental connexion?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The holy bible containing the old and the new testaments|year=1839|passage=Who feeds a flock, and makes not a '''merchandise''' of the sheep?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EUBAAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA14-PA2}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|archaic}} The act or business of trading; [[trade]]; [[traffic]].

