===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# A [[political]] [[philosophy]] [[opposed]] to the [[separation]] of a [[religious]] [[group]] (church) and a [[government]] (state), especially the belief held by those in 19th-century [[England]] [[opposed]] to separating the [[Anglican]] church from the [[civil]] government, or the [[w:separation of church and state|separation of church and state]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
#: {{ant|en|disestablishmentarianism}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1998|author=University of Oklahoma College of Law|title=American Indian Law Review|text=Jed Rubenfeld, who actually may not have been recycling a ''Boerne'' Court- rejected argument into a law review article,<sup>450</sup> reasoned that RFRA indeed lacked constitutionality, but because of First Amendment '''antidisestablishmentarianism''', and not the reasons offered by the Court.<sup>451</sup>}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|author=Angela Hague; David Lavery (credited as editors, but actually authors of the compiled fictional reviews)|title=Teleparody: predicting/preventing the TV discourse of tomorrow|text=The establishmentarianism of Hatch's alliance-building strategy undermined by the disestablishmentarianism of Wiglesworth's treachery triggers an '''antidisestablishmentarianism''' in Hawk &mdash; but the negation of Wiglesworth's 'dis' coupled with the counter-negation of Hawk's 'anti' does not simply generate a synthetic affirmation of Hatch's 'establishmentarianism'. Instead, Hawk's '''antidisestablishmentarianism''', like a cancerous wart on the end of the nose, is perched at the fuzzy border separating [[ontology]] from [[oncology]], [[malignity]] from [[malignancy]].}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2005-04-09|title=Crowning nonsense|newspaper=w:The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2005/apr/09/monarchy.guardianleaders|passage=As we said yesterday, the case for '''antidisestablishmentarianism''' has never been more threadbare.}}

