====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{senseid|en|be in command}} {{lb|en|transitive}} To be in command of. (See also {{m|en|head up}}.)
#: {{ux|en|Who '''heads''' the board of trustees?}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' an army, an expedition, or a riot}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To come at the beginning or front of; to [[commence]].
#: {{ux|en|A group of clowns '''headed''' the procession.}}
#: {{ux|en|The most important items '''headed''' the list.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1943|month=November and December|author=G. T. Porter|title=The Lines Behind the Lines in Burma|journal=Railway Magazine|page=325|text=When it arrived, the train was '''headed''' by a "K" class 4-6-0 wood-burning locomotive, and a water-tank wagon next to the tender was immediately besieged by women and girls, clad in their picturesque national costume, all with empty kerosene tins for water, a scene which was re-enacted at each stop down the line.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2018|author=James Lambert|title=Setting the Record Straight: An In-depth Examination of ''Hobson-Jobson''|journal=International Journal of Lexicography|volume=31|issue=4|doi=https://doi.org/10.1093/ijl/ecy010|page=491|text=The citations are set in smaller font, start on a new indented line and are '''headed''' with a date.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To strike with the head
#: {{co|en|to '''head''' the ball}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To move in a specified [[direction]].
#: {{syn|en|seek|bear}}
#: {{ux|en|We are going to '''head''' up North for our holiday.}}
#: {{ux|en|We will [['''head''' off]] tomorrow.}}
#: {{ux|en|Next holiday we will '''head out''' West, or '''head to''' Chicago.}}
#: {{ux|en|Right now I need to '''head''' into town to do some shopping.}}
#: {{ux|en|I'm fed up working for a boss. I'm going to '''head out''' on my own, set up my own business.}}
#: {{ux|en|Where does the train '''head''' to?}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=December|author=Voyageur|title=The Mountain Railways of the Bernese Oberland|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=752|text=To the left towers the Jungfrau, with the train '''heading''' directly towards it.}}
# {{lb|en|fishing|transitive}} To [[remove]] the head from (a fish).
#: {{cot|en|bone#Verb|debone#Verb|gut#Verb|scale#Verb|descale#Verb}}
#: {{nearsyn|en|behead#Verb|dehead#Verb}}
#: {{ux|en|The salmon are first '''headed''' and then scaled.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[originate]]; to [[spring]]; to have its course, as a river.
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1775|author=[[w:James Adair (historian)|James Adair]]|title=The History of the American Indians|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofamerica01adai/page/223/mode/1up|page=223
|passage=a broad purling river, that '''heads''' in the great blue ridge of mountains,}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1934|author=w:Henry G. Lamond|title=An Aviary on the Plains|publisher=Angus and Robertson|location=Sydney|page=156|passage=The Templeton '''heads''' in the Cloncurry ranges[.]}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To form a head.
#: {{ux|en|This kind of cabbage '''heads''' early.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Anne Raver|chapter=Gandhi Gardening|title=Deep in the Green: An Exploration of Country Pleasures|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Alfred A. Knopf|year=1995|isbn=978-0-307-82840-8|passage=To be honest, this hasn't been my Garden of Eden year. {{...}} The lettuce turned bitter and bolted. The Green Comet broccoli was good, but my coveted Romanescos never '''headed''' up.}}
# {{senseid|en|form a head on (hardware)}} {{lb|en|transitive|of hardware}} To form a head (on or to); to fit or furnish (something) with a head.
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a nail}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cut off the top of; to lop off.
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' trees}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[behead]]; to [[decapitate]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1822|author=[[w:Allan Cunningham (author)|Allan Cunningham]]|chapter=[[s:Traditional Tales of the English and Scottish Peasantry/Ezra Peden|Ezra Peden]]|title=Traditional Tales of the English and Scottish Peasantry|pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/traditionaltales01cunn#page/n55/mode/2up|volume=1|page=37
|passage=I tell thee, man of God, the uncharitableness of the sect to which thou pertainest has thronged the land of punishment as much as those who '''headed''', and hanged, and stabbed, and shot, and tortured.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Measure|2|1|passage=If you '''head''', and hang all that offend that way<br>but for ten yeare together; you'll be glad to giue out a<br>Commission for more heads}}
# To go in front of.
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a drove of cattle}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a person}}
# To get in the front of, so as to hinder or stop; to oppose.
#: {{ux|en|The wind '''headed''' the ship and made progress difficult.}}
# {{lb|en|by extension}} To [[check]] or [[restrain]].
# To set on the head.
#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a cask}}

