===Alternative forms===
* {{alt|en|punkin||US|term of endearment}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*pekʷ-}}
Alteration of {{m|en|pompion}}, {{m|en|pumpion|t=pumpkin}} with the diminutive {{affix|en|-kin<id:diminutive>}}, from {{der|en|frm|pompon}}, from {{der|en|la|pepō}} (whence {{cog|en|pepo}}), from {{der|en|grc|πέπων||large melon}}, from {{m|grc|πέπων||ripe}}, from {{m|grc|πέπτω||ripen}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=8260450369}}</ref> The first attestation is from 1647.<ref>{{cite-web |en |url=https://www.npr.org/2025/10/08/nx-s1-5563776/pumpkin-word-origin-history |title=Pumpkin: What's the word's origin and history? : NPR |publisher={{w|NPR}} |date=2025-10-08 |accessdate=2025-10-08 |first=Bill |last=Chappell |work=Word of the Week}}</ref>

The alternative theory that it may be from {{noncog|wam|pôhpukun||grows forth round}} is false.<ref>{{cite-web|titleurl=https://lldf.blogg.lu.se/debunking-a-myth-by-chunking-the-etymology-of-pumpkin/|title=Debunking a myth by chunking the etymology of pumpkin|work=Lund Language Diversity Forum – Lund University|author=Filip Larsson|date=November 12, 2021}}</ref>

The automotive sense is by fancied resemblance.

