===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|namen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|namian|t=to name, mention}} and {{m|ang|ġenamian|t=to name, call, appoint}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*namōn|t=to name}}. Cognate with {{cog|fy|neame|t=to name; to mention}}. Compare also {{cog|ang|nemnan}}, {{m|ang|nemnian|t=to name, give a name to a person or thing}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|ditransitive}} To [[give]] a name to.
#: {{ux|en|One visitor '''named''' Hou Yugang said he was not too concerned about climate change and Baishui’s melting.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1904|author=w:L. Frank Baum|title=The Land of Oz|passage=I will '''name''' the fellow 'Jack Pumpkinhead!'}}
#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=1|passage=A chap '''named''' Eleazir Kendrick and I had chummed in together the summer afore and built a fish-weir and shanty at Setuckit Point, down Orham way. For a spell we done pretty well.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[mention]], [[specify]].
#: {{ux|en|He '''named''' his demands.}}
#: {{ux|en|You '''name''' it!}}
#: {{ux|en|You have to pot the ball in the pocket you've '''named'''.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|title=UN Study: China, US, Japan Lead World AI Development|url=https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/un-study-china-us-japan-lead-world-ai-development/4769094.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207184548/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/un-study-china-us-japan-lead-world-ai-development/4769094.html|archivedate=7 February 2019|work=w:Voice of America|date=3 February 2019|passage=The three countries were '''named''' in a new study from the UN’s World Intellectual Property Organization, or WIPO. }}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[identify]] as relevant or important
#: {{ux|en|'''naming''' the problem}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To publicly [[implicate]] by name.
#: {{ux|en|The painter was '''named''' as an accomplice.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|of a person}} To disclose the name of.
#: {{ux|en|Police are not '''naming''' the suspect as he is a minor.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To designate for a [[role]].
#: {{syn|en|nominate}}
#: {{ux|en|My neighbor was '''named''' to the steering committee.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|Westminster system politics}} To initiate a process to temporarily remove a member of parliament who is breaking the rules of conduct.
#* {{quote-text|en|date=2013-07-10|author=[[w:John Bercow|John (Speaker of the House of Commons) Bercow]]|others=to MP {{w|Nigel Dodds}}|passage=I must warn the Right Honourable gentleman, that if he persists in his refusal to comply with my order to withdraw [the words "deliberately deceptive"], I shall be compelled to '''name''' him.}}

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|give a name to}} {{l|en|bename}}, {{l|en|designate}}, {{l|en|dub}}; see also [[Thesaurus:denominate]]
* {{sense|specify}} {{l|en|nominate}}; see also [[Thesaurus:specify]]

