==English==

===Etymology===
First used by {{w|Lewis Carroll}} in 1871, based on the concept of two words packed together, like a {{m|en|portmanteau|t=a travelling case having two halves joined by a hinge|id=luggage}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-portmanteau word.wav|a=Southern England}}

===Noun===
{{examples|
* {{m|en|brunch}}, formed from {{m|en|breakfast}} and {{m|en|lunch}}
* {{m|en|smog}}, formed from {{m|en|smoke}} and {{m|en|fog}}
}}
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A word which combines the meaning of two words (or, rarely, more than two words), formed by combining the words, usually, but not always, by adjoining the first part of one word and the last part of the other, the adjoining parts often having a common vowel.
#: {{syn|en
  |amalgamation<!-- synonym 1 -->
  |blend<!-- synonym 2 -->
  |id2=word<!-- target id for synonym 2 -->
  |brunch word<!-- synonym 3 -->
  |q3=dated<!-- qualifier for synonym 3 -->
  |frankenword<!-- synonym 4 -->
  |portmanteau<!-- synonym 5 -->
  |id5=word<!-- target id for synonym 5; note that synonym 5 is the 6th positional parameter passed to the {{syn}} template. -->
  |portmantologism<!-- synonym 6 -->
  |telescope word
}}
#* {{RQ:Carroll Looking-Glass|pages=126–127|pageref=127|passage=Well, ‘''slithy''’ means ‘lithe and slimy.’ ‘Lithe’ is the same as ‘active.’ You see it’s like a '''portmanteau'''⸺there are two meanings packed up into one word.|brackets=on}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1938|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xcAUAAAAIAAJ|title=Conversion and Fusion in Modern English: A Concise History of the Scholarly Recognition of These Linguistic Processes|author=Joane Chaffe Miller|text=He found the blend "tomax" in "a collection of gratulatory verses presented by the President and Fellows of Harvard College 1 to the new King, George III," dated 1761. A note by the owner of the volume explains the word as a combination of [[tomahawk]] and [[axe]]: "It is a '''portmanteau word''', which must have been as clear to the average reader in England of 1761 — as clear to George III himself - as brillig and slithy would have been to us, had not Humpty Dumpty kindly explained them."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1985|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=1JoCEI-H0DgC&pg=PA287|title=Selected Papers from the XIIIth Linguistic Symposium on Romance Languages, Chapel Hill, N.C., 24-26 March 1983|page=287|chapter=On the Representation of Higher Order Complex Words|author=Carlos Piera of Cornell University|text=1. '''Portmanteau Words''' and Allomorphy - This paper is primarily concerned with the theoretical implications of what have been called '''portmanteau words''' (Hockett, 1947)}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2018|author=James Lambert|title=A multitude of ‘lishes’: The nomenclature of hybridity|journal=English World-Wide|page=10|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/318367113_A_multitude_of_lishes_The_nomenclature_of_hybridity|text=One reason for the popularity of '''portmanteau words''' in naming language hybrids may be the fact that the names themselves embody a type of hybridity.}}

