==English==
{{wp}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰeh₂-|id=speak}}
From {{inh|en|enm|-}}, borrowed from {{der|en|fro|fable}}, from {{der|en|la|fābula}}, from {{m|la|for|fārī|to speak, say}} + {{m|la|-bula||instrumental suffix}}. See {{m|en|ban}}, and compare {{m|en|fabulous}}, {{m|en|fame}}. {{doublet|en|fabula}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|fā′bəl}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈfeɪbəl/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-fable.ogg|a=US}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪbəl|s=2}}
* {{hyphenation|en|fa|ble}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|Q693}}A [[fictitious]] [[narrative]] intended to [[enforce]] some useful [[truth]] or [[precept]], usually with [[animals]], etc. as [[characters]]; an [[apologue]]. Prototypically, [[w:Aesop's Fables|Aesop's Fables]].
#: {{syn|en|morality play}}
# Any story told to excite wonder; common talk; the [[theme]] of talk.
#: {{syn|en|legend}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|1 Timothy|4|7|page=1451|column=1|passage=But refuſe prophane and olde wiues '''fables''', and exerciſe thy ſelfe ''rather'' vnto godlineſſe.}}
#* {{RQ:Tennyson Poems 1842|II|The Gardener's Daughter; or, The Pictures|19|passage={{...}}we grew / The '''fable''' of the city where we dwelt.}}
# [[fiction|Fiction]]; [[untruth]]; falsehood.
#* {{RQ:Spectator|III|264|2 January 1712|316|I say it would look like a '''fable''' to report that this gentleman gives away all which is the overplus of a great fortune by secret methods to other men.}}
# The plot, story, or connected series of events forming the subject of an epic or dramatic poem.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1695|author=w:John Dryden|title=A Parallel betwixt Painting and Poetry|passage=For the moral (as Bossu observes,) is the first business of the poet, as being the groundwork of his instruction. This being formed, he contrives such a design, or '''fable''', as may be most suitable to the moral;}}

