===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|archaic}} To [[compose]] [[fables]]; hence, to write or speak [[fiction]]; to write or [[utter]] what is not true.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|IV|ii|111|2|He '''Fables''' not, I heare the enemie: / Out ſome light Horſemen, and peruſe their Wings.}}
#* {{RQ:Prior Poems|poem=An Ode, Humbly Inscrib’d to the Queen|stanza=XVII|page=287|passage=Vain now the Tales which '''fab’ling''' Poets tell, / That wav’ring ''Conqueſt'' ſtill deſires to rove; / In ''[[w:John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlbrô]]''’s Camp the Goddeſs knows to dwell: / Long as the Hero’s Life remains her Love.}}
#* '''1852''', {{w|Matthew Arnold}}, ''Empedocles on Etna'', Act II, in ''Empedocles on Etna and Other Poems'', London: B. Fellowes, p. 50,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/empedoclesonetna00arno]</sup>
#*: He '''fables''', yet speaks truth.
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[make up]]; to [[devise]], and speak of, as true or real; to tell of [[falsely]]; to [[recount]] in the form of a fable.
#: {{syn|en|make up|invent|feign|devise}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=VI|page=164|lines=288–292|passage={{...}} erre not that ſo ſhall end / The ſtrife of Glorie: which we mean to win, / Or turn this Heav’n itſelf into the Hell / Thou '''fableſt''' {{...}}|year=1873}}
#* {{quote-book|en|tlr=w:Arthur Gorges|chapter=Cassandra, or, Divination|title=The Wisdom of the Ancients|by=w:Francis Bacon|original=[De Sapientia Veterum]|location=London|year=1691|page=1|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/fessaysorcounsel00baco/page/1/mode/1up?view=theater|passage=THE ''Poets'' '''Fable''', That ''Apollo'' being enamoured of ''Caſſandra'', was by her many ſhifts and cunning ſlights ſtill deluded in his Deſire {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|page=24|passage='''Fabled''' by the daughters of memory. And yet it was in some way if not as memory '''fabled''' it. A phrase, then, of impatience, thud of Blake’s wings of excess.}}

