===Etymology 1===
{{ety|en|id=away|:inh|enm:a-<ety:inh<ang:ā->>}}
From {{inh|en|enm|a-|t=up, out, away}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ā-}}, originally {{m|ang|*ar-}}, {{m|ang|*or-}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*uʀ-}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*uz-|t=out-}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*uds-|t=up, out}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|a-}}, {{cog|de|er-}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-a-(1).ogg|a=US}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{senseid|en|up}}{{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss|Forming verbs with the sense ''away'', ''up'', ''on'', ''out''.}}
#: {{co|en|'''a'''rise, '''a'''wait}}
# {{senseid|en|asthough}}{{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss|Forming verbs with the sense of intensified action.}}
#: {{co|en|'''a'''bide, '''a'''maze}}

===Etymology 2===
{{ety|en|id=on|:inh|enm:a-<id:on><ety:from<an<id:on><ety:inh<ang:on>>>>}}
* From {{inh|en|enm|a-|t=on}}, derived from unstressed {{inh|en|enm|an|t=on}}, from {{inh|en|ang|an|t=on}}.
* See [[a]] {{qualifier|preposition|on, to, in, etc.}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-a-(1).ogg|a=US}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{senseid|en|having}}{{lb|en|rare|or|no longer productive}} [[in|In]], [[on]], [[at]]; {{italic|used to show a state, condition, or manner.  Also passing into sense 2.}}{{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley (2003)</ref>
#: {{co|en|'''a'''glow, '''a'''pace, '''a'''fire, '''a'''boil, '''a'''-bling, '''a'''bluster}}
# {{senseid|en|into}}{{lb|en|no longer productive}} In, into.  {{italic|Also passing into sense 5.}}{{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{co|en|'''a'''sunder}}
# {{senseid|en|toward}}In the direction of, or [[toward]]. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{co|en|'''a'''stern, '''a'''beam}}
# {{senseid|en|this}}{{lb|en|archaic|or|dialectal}} At such a time. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux|en|Come '''a'''-morning we are going hunting.}}
# {{senseid|en|doing}}{{lb|en|archaic|or|dialectal}} In the act or process of. {{italic|Used in some dialects before a present participle.  }}{{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{co|en|hits '''a-'''poppin}}
#: {{coi|en|doins '''a-'''transpirin|norm=doings '''a-'''transpiring}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1777|author=w:Thomas Arne|title=[[w:A-Hunting We Will Go|'''A'''-Hunting We Will Go]]|passage=}}
#* '''1780''', ''[[w:The Twelve Days of Christmas (song)|The Twelve Days of Christmas]]'':<!-- Traditional lyrics, as per The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes -->
#*: The twelfth day of Christmas,
#*: My true love sent to me
#*: Twelve lords '''a-'''leaping,
#*: …
#*: Eight maids '''a-'''milking,
#*: Seven swans '''a-'''swimming,
#*: Six geese '''a'''-laying,
#* circa '''1850''', ''{{w|Here We Come A-wassailing}}/Here We Come A-caroling''
#*: Here we come '''a-'''wassailing
#*: Among the leaves so green;
#*: Here we come '''a-'''wand’ring
#*: So fair to be seen.
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1939|author=w:Alfred Edward Housman|title=Additional Poems|section=XIII, lines 6-7|passage=Oh waste no words '''a-'''wooing<br>The soft sleep to your bed;}}
#* '''1947''', ''A NORTH-COUNTY DUBLIN CLOSSARY'':<ref>{{R:O'Neill 1947|page=263}}</ref>
#*: The hay is '''a-'''cutting now. You're '''a-'''wanting.
#* '''1964''', {{w|Bob Dylan}}, {{w|The Times They Are a-Changin' (song)|"The Times They Are a-Changin'&nbsp;"}} (recorded 1963, released 1964):
#*: The order is rapidly fadin'
#*: And the first one now will later be last
#*: For the times they are '''a-'''changin'
#* circa '''1970''', bumper sticker:<ref>See “[http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DontComeAKnockin Don’t Come A-Knockin’]”, ''TV Tropes'' for more examples and discussion.</ref>
#*: If the van’s '''a-'''rockin’, don’t come '''a-'''knockin’.

=====Usage notes=====
Adjectives formed with this prefix are often restricted to [[Appendix:Glossary#predicative|predicative]] use, owing to their origin as [[Appendix:Glossary#preposition|prepositional]] phrases with the preposition "on."  For example, one may say "the ship is ''afire,''" but not "the ''afire'' ship," just as one may say "the ship is ''on fire,''" but not "the ''on fire'' ship."

